n%20on%20it%20looking%20out%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F66428d25b4abc992e8c9284f%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%221500%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EThe%20city%20was%20covered%20by%20the%20hillside%2C%20but%20you%20could%20still%20see%20its%20light%20in%20the%20sky.%3Cp%3EMorgan%20McFall-Johnsen%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3ECompare%20that%20to%20the%20below%20picture%20that%20astrophotographer%20Dan%20Bartlett%20took%20about%20200%20miles%20east%20of%20me%2C%20in%20June%20Lake%2C%20California%2C%20near%20Yosemite.%20He%20was%20at%20roughly%20the%20same%20latitude%20but%20under%20much%20darker%20skies.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%221331%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22northern%20lights%20pink%20glow%20with%20spikes%20and%20green%20rim%20along%20the%20horizon%20in%20the%20night%20sky%20above%20a%20tree-lined%20lake%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F6642782bf27898f532d738a1%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22998%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EThe%20aurora%20came%20through%20much%20more%20clearly%2C%20with%20more%20structure%2C%20under%20the%20dark%20skies%20of%20June%20Lake%2C%20California.%3Cp%3EDan%20Bartlett%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EWhile%20he%20told%20me%20he%20spotted%20spikes%20and%20waves%20changing%20second%20by%20second%20with%20his%20naked%20eye%2C%20all%20I%20could%20see%20was%20a%20diffuse%20glow.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%221b9fa936-cc66-41ed-ad5f-7f356a3ea346%5C%22%3ECameras%20might%20also%20lie%20to%20you%20about%20the%20aurora's%20colors%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EAnother%20pitfall%20of%20seeing%20the%20aurora%20through%20a%20phone%20is%20that%20the%20colors%20aren't%20always%20true.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fastronaut-photo-aurora-from-international-space-station-2021-9%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ecolor%20of%20an%20aurora%3C%2Fa%3E%20indicates%20its%20altitude%2C%20as%20well%20as%20the%20type%20of%20molecules%20in%20the%20atmosphere%20that%20are%20creating%20it.%20Green%2C%20for%20example%2C%20usually%20comes%20from%20oxygen%20atoms%20at%20lower%20altitudes%20in%20the%20atmosphere.%20Pink%20or%20red%20can%20indicate%20high-altitude%20oxygen%20or%20nitrogen%20at%20very%20low%20altitudes.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EMy%20phone%20also%20picked%20up%20a%20field%20of%20purple%20in%20some%20images%2C%20which%20could%20indicate%20low-altitude%20nitrogen%20%E2%80%94%C2%A0but%20that%20could%20have%20been%20a%20trick%20of%20the%20pixels.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%222000%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22purple%20starry%20sky%20above%20treetops%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F664290319686a6f37bff8928%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%221500%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3ESome%20of%20my%20pictures%20turned%20out%20purple%20for%20some%20reason.%3Cp%3EMorgan%20McFall-Johnsen%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BObviously%2C%20screens%20do%20not%20always%20reproduce%20the%20natural%20colours%20reliably%2C%26quot%3B%20Maria%20Walach%2C%20a%20space%20plasma%20physicist%20who%20researches%20auroras%20at%20Lancaster%20University%2C%20told%20BI%20in%20an%20email.%20%26quot%3BAdditionally%2C%20you%20can%20get%20all%20sorts%20of%20colours%20from%20mixing%20and%20different%20viewing%20angles%2C%20which%20sometimes%20makes%20it%20tricky%20to%20tell.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAnd%2C%20of%20course%2C%20photos%20you%20see%20online%20could%20always%20be%20edited%20after%20the%20fact.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BDon't%20be%20misled.%20I%20mean%2C%20the%20camera%20does%20its%20own%20processing%20but%20you%20know%20that%20you%20could%20go%20in%20and%20change%20that%20processing%20level%20to%20your%20tastes%2C%26quot%3B%20Bartlett%20said.%20%26quot%3BYou%20could%20saturate%20the%20colors%20and%20make%20it%20grotesque%2C%20you%20could%20do%20anything%20you%20want%20with%20it.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%2